[Witness/Friend] That Time My Father-In-Law Was Wanted by Police (long)
WRITING.TEXT: My husband and I both come from middle class families and everyone on both sides are very straight-laced (we met at church, no one was into drugs or alcohol, etc.) My husband's dad is retired now, but when we first got married he held a fairly high position at a hospital. When he wasn't at work he was the Deacon at our church, always involved in leading Bible studies and so-forth. We'll say his dad's name is John. We married young so in our early years of marriage we were living in the not-so-great part of town. One day my husband was at school and my class hadn't started yet. As I was leisurely getting ready I hear a pounding at the door. Looking out, I see two police officers. I crack the door: gt; Can I help you? Is something wrong? "Yes," they say. "We're looking for John. Is he here?" My first thought was, well why the heck would they be looking for my father-in-law at my house...? I'm thinking he's hurt or missing or something, so I ask no more questions and immediately respond: gt; No, he should be at work! Is he okay? "Well," the officers respond, "he's wanted right now. Where does he work?" I'm panicking. What would my father-in-law be wanted for?! Some kind of... financial embezzlement?! After all, my in-laws just took a nice vacation... I tell the officers where he works and immediately start trying to call him, but he's not answering. Not much later, the officers are back. "We were just at XYZ Hospital and they say John doesn't work there. Can we come in and take a look around?" WHAT. THE. HECK. Are these guys even real? Here I am, a month past my 19th birthday in a seedy part of town... So I asked the officers to give me a moment so I could call dispatch and I shut the door. At this point, I imagine they thought I was trying to hide my father-in-law. After confirming that the officers were legitimate I let them in. They looked around, under beds, in closets, etc. Finally I asked them what my father-in-law was wanted for, but they wouldn't tell me. Now I'm thinking it's REALLY bad. They asked me again why my father-in-law works. I told them, the same as before, XYZ hospital. There's some back and forth, me saying gt; Talk to Matt, the security guard! I was JUST there last week! Finally, one of the officers says, "We DID speak to Matt, and he says John Doe doesn't work there!" Wait. John. Doe? My father-in-law's last name is Smith... I showed the officer's my marriage certificate to confirm the last name, and they said they had some additional checking to do. I never heard back from them, so I assume they realized my father-in-law was innocent. But, for half a day at least, my super straight-laced, church-attending father-in-law was a fugitive from the law.

WRITING.TEXT: ETA: answered. Many thanks for the good tips! Hope it's okay to post this here, since I mostly see posts more intended for game comments and stuff... if there's a better sub to post my question in, please direct me! So I recently got FO4 because I was enjoying Skyrim so much. But I'm really having a hard time with it. I love the story and gameplay so far, but I'm having trouble with some basic things. For example, the weapons. There are just *so many* choices. Is there a decent weapon that I can use as a "every day carry" type gun and then just switch to a special gun for special situations (e.g. find something really long range for those times when I'm fighting raiders who are at a distance from me or something). Any weapons that are just basically useless that I can drop/not pick up? Also, the perks system... ack, I'm just overwhelmed. I'm curious to hear other people's experiences with how you upgrade your perks (evenly across the board / focus on building up just a couple). Finally, does anyone play without using chems? I have a ton that I've collected but I'm kind of confused about whether or not I should use them because they're "addictive." Are they detrimental if you use too many? I know these are probably kind of dumb questions, but I'd love any input! I'm not opposed to trial and error, and I love the open world and just wandering around... so if it's just kind of a "play a ton and you'll figure it out" type deal, I'm cool with that. But if anyone can give me some "must-know" tips, that would be helpful. Thanks!

WRITING.TITLE: Your dream TES game: where would it be set?
WRITING.TEXT: I was thinking last night that I would love to see a prequel-esque game, set in the early days of Tamriel (probably Morrowind with some DLCs added later to include other locations) before the downfall of the Dwemer. I'd like to be able to play as either a Nord or Dwemer, and the acts of the game would follow the downfall of the Dwemer society. (I don't know how popular that would be, since you can't change the past and no matter what you did if you're playing as a Dwemer, you essentially lose in the end). I think there would be a lot of potential in the game, since the Dwemer were known for being creative and industrious. I bet it could take a lot of the building and creating aspects from FO4, where you could essentially build parts of the city-states that now (ruined) dot the landscape of Tamriel. I think it would also be a neat, immersive way to learn some of the backstory, which is still shrouded in mystery. I'm curious what others would like to see, location, era, lore, etc.

WRITING.TITLE: Sprint will not unlock my phone
WRITING.TEXT: UPDATE and "What worked": I think a combo attack worked here, using advice from both /u/T-MobileCustomer2017 and /u/stylz168. The rep in OKC was more helpful than any of the other dozens of customer care reps I'd spoken to previously. He took the time to look through my entire account, see all the tickets, and find out why they were being rejected even though on the surface everything showed that my device was eligible. He fixed the problem, only to have another "unlock denied" email follow 30 minutes later. At that point, I was confident that *nothing* should be holding my devices in Sprint limbo anymore. I contacted Marci's team who called me at 10PM (after getting my permission to call me after 9). He reviewed everything and confirmed that there was absolutely no reason my devices should still be locked. He assured me that they would definitely be unlocked within 48 hours, but probably sooner. When I woke up this morning I decided to give my new SIM card a shot and, lo and behold, they were unlocked! **TL;DR:** Do *not* let Sprint bully you into keeping your devices locked to their service! Go through the proper procedures to unlock your device first, but if they are not unlocked within 48 hours, try the OKC/Marci approach! --- I got my phone last December on a lease from Sprint. My Sprint service has been very bad and only getting worse, so I decided to pay off my phone and the lease and everything so I could switch to Verizon. But I have been dealing with getting my phone unlocked for five days. They keep saying they #8217;ll unlock it, but then I get an email saying my device is ineligible. Then I call and they say it #8217;s eligible and they #8217;ll unlock it. Then the email. I went into my local store and they were completely unhelpful. Today (day five), I had someone tell me I owed them for this month #8217;s service but my account balance is 0 and Sprint actually canceled my service yesterday without my consent. So I don #8217;t even have service now. I #8217;m at the end of my rope. Online searches conclude that many, many other people have encountered these same problems. What do I do?
